How to add CSS?

There are three ways in which we can add css.

1) Inline - <tag style="css" />
2) Internal - <style>css<style>
3) External - <link href="style.css">

These are the different styles

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Inline Style of adding css
-- It goes into the same line as a particular HTML element

eg:
<html style = "background: blue">
</html>

In this case, the inline css goes into the opening tag of the html, we got a style attribute
which is globally availably, and any tag we can add style attribute too

it goes like this
<all tags name of the style = value>
value is in two parts
property we wanna change and the value separated by a color.

inline elements are useful to add css to single element to our page.

It's not normally recommended to use inline


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Internal CSS --
This is done through a special HTML tag called the style element,
we got an open & closing style tag, and in between those two lines, we add
all our css

eg -> this is our css
html{
     background: red;
    }


<html>
    <head>
        <style>
            html{
                background: red;
            }
        </style>
    </head>
</html>

previously we have it in our tag, this one is extra, here, our internal style can be applied inside html document to any element.
what we have to add in edition is a selector, this selector comes before a set of curly braces and the css
comes within the curly braces.
{
    css
}
like this.

our internal styling can be applied to anywhere in our HTML document, and inside we can target or select
as many elements as we want.

The code is limited in the html that it sits in, which means that if we have a multi page
website, then we probably shouldn't be using the internal style.

Instead
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

We should use external styling CSS

External CSS --

The biggest difference between the external, and the internal, and inline styles is that this
actually lives in a completely separate file. eg. main.css, styles.css, which as a .css as extension.

Inside the css, we write out css rules,

we got the selector, the properties, values and many many things.


we have to link up the html and css
inside the head section, we add a link element,

eg
<link
    rel="stylesheet"    # tells the relationship
    href="./styles.css" # tells the location of the css
/>

This style is most commonly using in html,

inline is useful for targetting single element
internal is useful for single webpage
external is useful when we have multiple files and websites, most often used method of styling 
